   BBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBB";
       size_t len = strlen(str);
       printf("%s\n", str + len);
   }
   
   Observed symptom: memory access outside the bounds of the `str` array.
   The bug arises from accessing `str` with an index `len` that exceeds the
   array's bounds, resulting in an out-of-bounds memory access.
   
   ROOT CAUSE:
   program.c:25: Accessing `str` with an out-of-bounds index `len` due to
   incorrect length calculation.
   
   LOCAL FIX:
   ```c
   char *str = " BBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBBB";
   size_t len = strlen(str);
   printf("%s\n", str); // Remove the out-of-bounds access
   ```
   
   GLOBAL FIX:
   Replace `printf("%s\n", str + len);` with `printf("%s\n", str);`. The
   `strlen` function already calculates the length of the string, including the
   null-terminator. Accessing `str + len` skips the null-terminator and leads to
   undefined behavior.
   
   This is due to the null-terminator being included in the `strlen` count. The
   correct fix is to print the original `str` pointer, not the pointer to the
   character after the last valid character.
